  "prompt": "Where can I find comedic monologues from published plays?",
  "response": "Finding comedic monologues from published plays can be an exciting way to explore various characters and styles. Here are some resources and methods to help you find them:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Play Collections and Anthologies**\n- **Best Plays Collections**: Look for anthologies like \"The Best American Short Plays\" or \"The Best Women\u2019s Stage Monologues\" series, which often include comedic monologues.\n- **Comedy Play Anthologies**: Collections like \"Great Monologues for Young Actors\" or \"Audition Monologues for Men/Women\" often feature humorous pieces.\n- **Sampler Books**: Books like \"Comic Monologues That Are Actually Funny\" by David Dalton can be a great starting point.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Published Plays**\n- **Classic Comedies**: Explore plays by writers like Neil Simon (\"The Odd Couple\"), Oscar Wilde (\"The Importance of Being Earnest\"), or Moli\u00e8re (\"Tartuffe\").\n- **Contemporary Comedies**: Look for works by playwrights like Christopher Durang, David Lindsay-Abaire, or Theresa Rebeck.\n- **One-Act Plays**: These often contain concise and humorous monologues, as seen in works by authors like David Ives or Don Zolidis.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Online Resources**\n- **Monologue Databases**: Websites like *Monologue Archive* or *StageAgent* categorize monologues by genre, including comedy.\n- **Playwright Websites**: Some playwrights, like Ken Ludwig or Don Zolidis, offer monologues from their works on their personal websites.\n- **Public Domain Plays**: Sites like *Project Gutenberg* or *Internet Archive* have classic comedies that are free to access.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Libraries and Bookstores**\n- **Drama Section**: Check the drama or theater section of your local library or bookstore for collections of comedic plays.\n- **Interlibrary Loan**: If your library doesn\u2019t have the play you\u2019re looking for, they may be able to borrow it from another library.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Theater Groups and Workshops**\n- **Local Theater Companies**: Many theater groups have libraries of scripts you can borrow or purchase.\n- **Acting Classes**: Instructors often have resources for comedic monologues and can recommend specific plays.\n\n---\n\n### **6. YouTube and Streaming Platforms**\n- **Performances**: Watch performances of comedic plays to identify monologues that resonate with you.\n- **Acting Channels**: Some YouTube channels focus on monologues and may feature humorous ones.\n\n---\n\n### **7. Social Media and Forums**\n- **Facebook Groups**: Join theater or acting groups where members share resources and recommendations.\n- **Reddit**: Subreddits like r/Theatre or r/Acting often have threads discussing monologue sources.\n\n---\n\nBy exploring these resources, you\u2019ll likely find a wide variety of comedic monologues that suit your needs!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
